            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was 16, holding the TIG torch for the first time in his high school metal shop. He eased off the foot pedal, lifted the dark shield, and stared at the two pieces of scrap steel. They were no longer two, but one. The seam was crude, but it was permanent and strong. In the acrid smell of ozone and the dim glow of the cooling metal, calculus and parental expectations dissolved. This felt more true, more real than anything from a textbook. It was the moment he found his native language.\n\n2.\nAt 18, sitting at the kitchen table in their Sunset home, he pushed the trade school pamphlet towards his parents. The silence that followed was heavier than any argument. He saw the deep disappointment in his father\u2019s eyes and watched his mother\u2019s hands tremble slightly as she folded a napkin. It was a quiet, painful act of rebellion, choosing his own path over their dreams for him. In that moment of their heartbreak, he felt his own spine harden into something unbending, something forged in conviction.\n\n3.\nHis first foreman in the Bayview shop, a gruff old-timer named Sal, rarely spoke. At 22, Aaron spent a week perfecting a series of complex welds on a custom staircase railing. Sal inspected the work, running a calloused thumb over the seamless joints. He didn\u2019t look at Aaron\u2019s face, but at his hands. \"Alright, Malhotra,\" was all he said, a single, sharp nod of approval. That quiet, professional respect from a man of the craft meant more to him than any diploma ever could. It was when he stopped being a kid.\n\n4.\nHe remembers a specific evening at the brewery last year, his knuckles raw from a new project. A furniture designer he knew sat down, nodding to the fresh burn on his forearm. \"The work leaves its mark,\" she\u2019d said, showing him a silver scar on her own palm from a chisel slip. There was no pity, only shared understanding. In that simple gesture, he felt a profound sense of belonging he\u2019d never felt in advanced placement classes\u2014a community where calluses and scars were badges of honor, not signs of failure.\n\n5.\nRiding his Bonneville home a few months ago, he saw it: a grimy, forgotten workshop down an alley in the Dogpatch with a faded \"For Lease\" sign. He killed the engine, the sudden silence filled with a roaring possibility. He could already smell the hot steel and see the sparks flying from a grinder in the dim light. It wasn't just an empty building; it was the physical shape of his future. The name \"Malhotra Metalworks\" stopped being a dream and became a blueprint waiting to be built."
